sublevels.theory:
The `switch` statement compares a variable against constant values (`case` labels). `break` exits the switch; without it, execution **falls through** to the next case.

```cpp
int day = 4;
switch (day) {
  case 1: std::cout << "Monday"; break;
  case 2: std::cout << "Tuesday"; break;
  default: std::cout << "Other day"; break;
}
```

- The expression must evaluate to an **integral type** (`int`, `char`, `enum`)
- `default` runs when no case matches — optional but recommended
- Stack multiple cases for the same code block by listing them consecutively

**Switch with `enum`:**
```cpp
enum class Color { Red, Green, Blue };
switch (color) {
  case Color::Red:   ...; break;
  case Color::Green: ...; break;
  case Color::Blue:  ...; break;
}
```

**`[[fallthrough]]` attribute (C++17)** — explicitly marks intentional fall-through to silence compiler warnings:
```cpp
case 2:
    doPartialWork();
    [[fallthrough]];
case 3:
    doRest();
    break;
```

**Switch-init (C++17):** `switch (int n = compute(); n) { ... }` — like if-init, scopes variable to the switch.

**Pattern matching is NOT (yet) in C++ switch** — unlike Rust/Python `match`, C++ switch only tests equality. Pattern matching proposals are in progress.

**`std::visit` (C++17)** — a functional alternative for variant types:
```cpp
std::visit(overloaded{
    [](int i) { std::cout << "int: " << i; },
    [](std::string s) { std::cout << "str: " << s; }
}, myVariant);
```

**Duff's device** — an extreme (unusual) use of intentional fall-through for loop unrolling using switch.

**Performance note:** Switches over dense integral ranges are typically compiled to jump tables (O(1)); sparse ranges may fall back to if-chains.
